# -*- mode: org -*-
#+TITLE: build system: correctness, parallelism, portability
#+DATE: 2026-06-20

* DONE [#B] makedir: build-system correctness + portability  :build:make:
  RESOLUTION (2026-06-20):
  - ifeq (`uname`,...): fixed the remaining instances to ifeq ($(TARGET),...)
    (bolib's was fixed with the POSIX-timer work; bplib's commented block here).
  - targetLinux: de-hardcoded /usr/bin/gcc, /usr/bin/g++ to gcc/g++ (honour
    $PATH); LD now defaults to $(CCPLUS) so C++/Objective-C programs link with
    the C++ driver (and its runtime) instead of the C driver.
  - Added an "uninstall" target (registered in common-targets, implemented in
    makedir/common): removes $(PREFIX)/lib/$(MODULE) and the module's installed
    programs, guarded so an empty PREFIX/MODULE can never expand to a
    destructive rm. Validated: make uninstall removes all 7 modules' trees.
  Verified the full clean build still produces all 7 libraries with the new
  compiler settings.

  DEFERRED (intentionally not changed --- the single-pass "make depend; make;
  make install" works, and these are riskier refactors that could destabilise it):
  - Making Makefile.depend a restartable include and adding inter-module
    dependencies so "make -j" is safe across modules. For now the documented
    sequence is single-threaded.
  - Replacing the apply/"gcc -M" dependency generation with "$(CC) -MM -MT".
  - Removing the "|| true" that masks install failures (changing it risks
    breaking installs on systems with unusual permissions).
  - Deleting the obsolete library/program/*-template makefiles and the stale
    ribtest Makefile; the %:%.c / %:%.cc single-source link patterns.
  The makedir/README staleness is tracked in doc-readme-fixes.

== Original findings ==

Already fixed (do not re-do): absolute =APPLY=$(MAKEDIR)/apply=; =install:: all=;
cross-module =-I= paths; =MAKEDIR=/=COMMON= derived from the Makefile's own path
(=sudo make install= now works).

** Findings — correctness

*** [high] ifeq (`uname`,Darwin) never matches — platform sources dropped (bolib/sources/Makefile:59,63; bplib/sources/Makefile:84)
=ifeq= compares *strings at parse time* and does not run a shell, so the
backticks are literal: =ifeq (`uname`,Darwin)= is always false. On Darwin,
=BoTimer.next.m= is never added to =OBJCSOURCES= (yet =BoTimer.h= is still
installed — header with no implementation). Fix: =ifeq ($(TARGET),Darwin)=
(=TARGET= is already =$(shell uname)=) or =ifeq ($(shell uname),Darwin)=.

*** [high] all :: depend libraries programs is order-unsafe; reason for the historic two-pass (makedir/common:117)
=Makefile.depend= is pulled with =-include= at parse time; on a clean tree it is
absent, so the first build has no header deps, and the file built by a recipe of
=all= is not re-read in the same run. This is why a second =make depend= / =make=
was historically needed. Under =make -j= the three =::= prerequisites are
unordered, so =libraries=/=programs= can compile while =depend= is still writing.
Fix: make =Makefile.depend= a proper *restartable include* (=include
Makefile.depend= + a rule to build it), or drop =depend= from =all= and order it.

*** [high] No inter-module ordering — parallel install races (makedir/common:186; project:52-71)
Tests link against the *installed* libs (=bplib/tests/BpDictTest/sources/
Makefile:79= → =$(PREFIX)/lib/bplib/…=) and =bplib= needs =bclib=. The recursion
gives make no edges between modules, so =make -j install= can build a dependent
before its prerequisite is installed. The ordered =MODULES= list is not enough.
Fix: add explicit module-level dependencies.

*** [medium] LD = $(CC) links C++/ObjC programs with the C driver (targetLinux:52; common:153)
A C++ program without an explicit =_LD= links with =gcc= (no C++ runtime). The
tests work around it with =BpDictTest_LD=$(CCPLUS)= — proving the default is a
footgun. Fix: pick =LD= from the languages present, or document it as mandatory.

*** [medium] install recipes mask failures with || true (common:189,195,201,207,218; program:106; library:101-106)
=mkdir … 2>/dev/null || true= and =install … || true= swallow real errors
(permission denied, read-only =$(PREFIX)=), so a failed install reports success.
Drop the blanket =|| true= and let errors propagate.

*** [medium] dependency generation via apply/gcc -M is fragile (makedir/apply:46,51-53; common:223-236)
=echo $* | xargs … $command= re-splits and globs unquoted flags; the BSD
fallback re-invokes the compiler per file; =gcc -M= (not =-MM=) pulls system
headers and breaks on a not-yet-generated header (e.g. =version.h=) or paths with
spaces. Fix: generate deps with =$(CC) -MM -MT $@ -MF= directly per source and
retire =apply=; consider =-MG=.

** Findings — portability / cruft

*** [medium] Hardcoded /usr/bin/gcc, /usr/bin/g++ (targetLinux:58,68,78)
Absolute paths ignore =$PATH= and break on Nix/cross/clang-only systems.
=targetDarwin= correctly uses bare =gcc=. Use =CC=gcc=/=cc= and let users override.

*** [low] % : %.c / % : %.cc link patterns can mislink (targetLinux:64-65,84-85)
These single-source "build an exe from one source" rules can be picked instead of
the intended =$(..._OBJECTS)=/=$(..._LIBRARIES)= rule. Prefer deleting them.

*** [low] Obsolete cruft to remove or mark
=makedir/library= and =makedir/program= =all::= print "deprecated… exit 1" after
building; =*-template-makefile= and =bprib/tests/ribtest/sources/Makefile=
(references nonexistent =cc++=, =-arch m68k=, =$(COMMON)/cplusplus/…=) are stale
and confusing. No =uninstall= target exists; installs accumulate.

** Findings — documentation (see also doc-readme-fixes)
=makedir/README= documents variables (=SUBPROJECT=/=PROGRAMNAME=/=LIBRARYNAME=)
that the Makefiles no longer use (real ones: =MODULES=/=PROGRAMS=/=LIBRARIES=/
=*_OBJECTS=/=*_LIBRARIES=). The two-pass-depend requirement, cross-module install
order, =TARGET=→=target<NAME>= mapping, default =PREFIX=/usr/local=, and the
=-Werror -pedantic-errors= strictness are all undocumented.

** Plan
1. Fix the three =ifeq (`uname`,…)= sites (highest leverage, silent on Darwin).
2. Make =Makefile.depend= a restartable include (kills the two-pass need) and add
   inter-module dependencies so =make -j= is safe.
3. Switch dep generation to =$(CC) -MM=; drop =apply=.
4. Default =LD= sensibly; remove =|| true=; de-hardcode the compiler paths.
5. Remove/mark obsolete makefiles; add an =uninstall= target.
6. Rewrite =makedir/README= to match reality (folds into doc-readme-fixes).
